14_1	0.133829	If the findings are verified, they suggest scientists should study whether the aspirin some heart patients take might also help overweight people reduce their chances of heart attacks.
14_2	0.17045243	Being overweight is an automatic warning sign for heart disease: The fatter people are, the more likely they are to have high cholesterol and clogged arteries, high blood pressure, diabetes and other cardiovascular risk factors.
14_3	0.07514141	But no one knew if those extra pounds could cause yet another risk: low-grade inflammation inside a person's arteries.
14_4	0.092994573	In otherwise seemingly healthy people, scientists recently discovered that this low-grade inflammation can simmer for years and significantly increase a person's risk of a heart attack or stroke.
14_5	0.077014635	No one knows what causes the subtle inflammation.
14_6	0.10235974	One theory has been that it might be bacteria, and indeed, some research suggests that antibiotics may help fight heart disease.
14_7	0.079112203	On the other hand, doctors already frequently prescribe aspirin to certain people at high risk of heart attacks because it thins their blood --and aspirin also reduces inflammation.
14_8	0.079127926	Dutch scientist Marjolein Visser knew that fat cells themselves can produce a substance called interleukin-6 that causes inflammation when it seeps into the bloodstream.
14_9	0.092372733	So she studied whether obesity could be another culprit, using a U.S. database of 16,000 Americans.
14_10	0.079806655	The only way to measure this ``micro-inflammation'' is using a blood test that detects C-reactive protein, or CRP.
14_11	0.10382708	CRP levels skyrocket when people are sick, with colds, inflammatory diseases like rheumatoid arthritis, even heart disease.
14_12	0.084893333	But lower levels, between 0.2 milligrams and 1 mg per deciliter of blood, are the ones that signal the simmering inflammation that has scientists concerned.
14_13	0.11385624	Visser discovered that obese women are six times more likely to have this low-grade inflammation than normal-weight people.
14_14	0.12291838	Obese men were twice as likely to have it, a gender difference Visser couldn't explain, except to say that women in the study were much more overweight than men studied.
14_15	0.087708766	``We were surprised'' the risk was so high, Visser said Tuesday, before presenting her findings at a biology meeting here.
14_16	0.091989605	If verified, ``it could have quite an impact''.
14_17	0.094489035	Visser, a weight specialist at Amsterdam's Vrije University, statistically controlled for other diseases that might have caused the study participants' CRP levels to rise.
14_18	0.090945336	She found equal risk when examining only healthy people under age 40.
14_19	0.093808258	Even ``at a young age, when you're obese there's this inflammation, and we know it's bad for you,'' she said.
14_20	0.14725715	The study isn't proof that obesity inflames people's arteries, cautioned Dr.
14_21	0.10007859	Richard J.
14_22	0.18596252	Havlik of the National Institute on Aging, which funded the research.
